ng 2017-05 FC Bayern Muenchen-3 (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = M\u00fcller training with [[Bayern Munich]] in 2017\n| fullname            = Thomas M\u00fcller<ref name=\"FIFA Club World Cup Morocco 2013: List of Players\" />\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1989|9|13|df=y}}<ref name=\"FIFA Club World Cup Morocco 2013: List of Players\">{{Cite news| title = FIFA Club World Cup Morocco 2013: List of Players| url = http://www.fifadata.com/document/FCWC/2013/pdf/FCWC_2013_SquadLists.pdf| publisher = FIFA| format = PDF| page = 5| date = 7 December 2013| accessdate = 8 December 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Weilheim in Oberbayern]], West Germany\n| height              = 1.86 m<ref name=\"FCBprofile\"/>\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| clubnumber          = 25\n| youthyears1         = 1993\u20132000\n| youthclubs1         = TSV P\u00e4hl\n| youthyears2         = 2000\u20132008\n| youthclubs2         = [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]]\n| years1              = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs1              = [[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]\n| caps1               = 35\n| goals1              = 16\n| years2              = 2008\u2013\n| clubs2              = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| caps2               = 343<!--DOMESTIC LEAGUE APPS ONLY -->\n| goals2              = 116<!--DOMESTIC LEAGUE GOALS ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1      = 2004\u20132005\n| nationalteam1       = [[Germany national youth football team|Germany U16]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 6\n| nationalgoals1      = 0\n| nationalyears2      = 2007\n| nationalteam2       = [[Germany national youth football team|Germany U19]]\n| nationalcaps2       = 3\n| nationalgoals2      = 0\n| nationalyears3      = 2008\n| nationalteam3       = [[Germany national youth football team|Germany U20]]\n| nationalcaps3       = 1\n| nationalgoals3      = 1\n| nationalyears4      = 2009\n| nationalteam4       = [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany U21]]\n| nationalcaps4       = 6\n| nationalgoals4      = 1\n| nationalyears5      = 2010\u2013<!--Do not add the end year until the player OFFICIALLY announces their national team retirement-->\n| nationalteam5       = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps5       = 100\n| nationalgoals5      = 38\n| club-update         = 16:24, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:41, 19 November 2018 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates      =\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|GER}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men\u2019s [[association football|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 Brazil]]|}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 Poland\u2013Ukraine]]|}}<!--Though there was no third place playoff, UEFA decided in the 2012 edition to award the semi-final losers (Germany and Portugal) bronze medals for the first time: https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/competitions/euro/91/87/57/918757_download.pdf-->\n{{Medal|3rd|[[UEFA Euro 2016|2016 France]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas M\u00fcller''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8to\u02d0mas \u02c8m\u028fl\u0250}}; born 13 September 1989) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for and [[Captain (association football)|vice-captains]] [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], and has made 100 appearances for the [[Germany national football team|German national team]]. A versatile player, M\u00fcller plays as a [[midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)|forward]], and has been deployed in a variety of attacking roles \u2013 as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]], [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]] and on either [[Midfielder#Winger|wing]]. He has been praised for his positioning, teamwork and stamina, work-rate, and has shown consistency in both scoring and creating goals.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=1001343 | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | language = German | publisher = DFB | access-date = 18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nA product of Bayern's [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|youth system]], he made his first-team breakthrough in the [[2009\u201310 FC Bayern Munich season|2009\u201310 season]] after [[Louis van Gaal]] was appointed as the main coach; he played almost every game as the club won the [[2009\u201310 Bundesliga|league]] and [[2009\u201310 DFB-Pokal|cup]] [[Double (association football)|double]] and reached the [[2010 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]]. M\u00fcller scored 23 goals in the 2012\u201313 season as Bayern won a historic [[Treble (association football)|treble]]; the league title, cup and [[2013 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League]].\n\nM\u00fcller earned a call-up to the German national team in 2010. At the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] he scored five goals in six appearances as Germany finished in [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Third place play-off|third place]]. He was named the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Best Young Player Award|Best Young Player]] of the tournament and won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] as the tournament's top scorer, with five goals and three [[Assist (football)|assists]]. At the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] he played a major role in helping the team win the trophy, scoring five goals and receiving the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Silver Ball]] as the tournament's second top player and the [[FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe#Golden Boot|Silver Boot]] as the second top goalscorer, and was also named in the [[FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe#All-Star Team|World Cup All Star XI]] and in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup awards#Dream Team|Dream Team]].\n\nIn 2014, M\u00fcller was ranked the fifth-best footballer in the world by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2014/dec/21/the-top-100-footballers-2014-interactive|title=The top 100 footballers 2014 \u2013 interactive|date=21 December 2014|work=The Guardian | access-date = 18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Weilheim in Oberbayern|Weilheim]], M\u00fcller played as a youth for TSV P\u00e4hl, and at the age of 10<ref name=\"Muller claims he turned down 'astronomical' Man United offer\">{{cite news|last=Lynch|first=David|title=Muller claims he turned down 'astronomical' Man United offer|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/muller-claims-turned-down-astronomical-7642557|accessdate=20 August 2014|publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> he made the {{convert|50|km|mi|adj=on}} journey to join local [[Bundesliga]] side Bayern Munich in 2000.<ref name=\"FCBprofile\">{{cite web|url= http://www.fcbayern.de/de/teams/profis/thomas-mueller/index.php |title=Thomas M\u00fcller|publisher=[[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]| accessdate = 17 August 2014 | language = de}}</ref> He progressed through the [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|youth system]] and was part of the team that finished runner-up in the [[Under 19 Bundesliga]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://team.dfb.de/de/das-team/mittelfeld/thomas-mueller/biografie/page/1378.html?1313584142 | title = Biografie | language = de | publisher = DFB | accessdate = 17 August 2014}}</ref> He made his debut for the [[FC Bayern Munich II|reserve team]] in March 2008 when he replaced [[Stephan F\u00fcrstner]] in a [[Regionalliga]] match against [[SpVgg Unterhaching]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/2008/ |publisher=fussballdaten.de |title=Spiele von Thomas M\u00fcller in 2007/2008| language = German |accessdate=28 January 2010|trans-title=Appearances by Thomas M\u00fcller in the 2007\u20132008 season}}</ref> in which he scored. He made two more Regionalliga appearances in the 2007\u201308 season,<ref name=\"2007\u201308 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2007-08/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref> while continuing to play for the under-19 team. The following season, Bayern's second string qualified for the newly formed [[3. Liga]], and M\u00fcller established himself as a key player \u2013 he played in 32 out of 38 matches<ref name=\"fussballdaten0809\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/2009/|publisher=fussballdaten.de|title=Spiele von Thomas M\u00fcller in 2008/2009|accessdate=28 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=Appearances by Thomas M\u00fcller in the 2008\u20132009 season}}</ref> and scored 15 times<ref name=\"Spieler-Statistik 2008/09\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2008-09/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref> to make him the league's fifth top scorer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/dritteliga/2009/statistik/#Tore|title=Torj\u00e4ger der 3. Liga 2008/2009|publisher=fussballdaten.de|accessdate=28 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=3rd Liga Top Goalscorers 2008\u20132009}}</ref> He also became involved in the first-team under then manager [[J\u00fcrgen Klinsmann]]; he appeared in pre-season friendlies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/matchreport/2008/17116.php |title=Polished Bayern send out signal to rivals |date=31 July 2008 |publisher=Bayern Munich |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319023228/http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/matchreport/2008/17116.php |archivedate=19 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/matchreport/2008/17167.php|title=Below-strength FCB undone by wily Italians| publisher=Bayern Munich|date= 5 August 2008|accessdate=28 January 2010}}</ref> and made his full debut on 15 August 2008, when he came on as a substitute for [[Miroslav Klose]] for the last ten minutes of a [[Bundesliga]] match against [[Hamburger SV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2008-09/1/863397/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_hamburger-sv-12.html|title=Trochowski belohnt Hamburger Moral| work = [[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date= 15 August 2008|accessdate=23 June 2011|language=German|trans-title=Trochowski rewards Hamburg's team spirit}}</ref> Despite M\u00fcller feeling that his performance did not go well,<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> he made three more Bundesliga appearances that season<ref name=\"fussballdaten0809\" /> and made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut on 10 March 2009 when he was substituted on in the 72nd minute for [[Bastian Schweinsteiger]] in a 7\u20131 win over [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]. He scored Bayern's last goal as they won the tie 12\u20131 on [[Aggregate score|aggregate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/mar/10/championsleague-bayernmunich?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Bayern's deadly dozen piles on humiliation for Sporting Lisbon| website = [[The Guardian]] |date= 10 March 2009|accessdate=23 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Bayern Munich===\nIn February 2009, M\u00fcller signed his first contract for the senior team, a two-year deal effective from the [[2009\u201310 FC Bayern Munich season|2009\u201310 season]], along with reserve teammate [[Holger Badstuber]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/de/aktuell/news/2009/18613.php|title=Badstuber und M\u00fcller unterschreiben|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=16 February 2009|accessdate=31 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=Badstuber and M\u00fcller sign}}</ref>\n\n====2009\u201310 season====\n{{See also|2009\u201310 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n\nM\u00fcller was prepared to be loaned or even transferred away to find first-team football,<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> but when [[Louis van Gaal]] was appointed manager, both M\u00fcller and Badstuber became fixtures in the Bayern first team from the start of the season.<ref name=\"fussballdaten0910\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/2010/ |publisher=fussballdaten.de | language = German |title=Spiele von Thomas M\u00fcller in 2009/2010 |accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref> In the first few matches, M\u00fcller was a regular substitute, and on 12 September 2009, he was brought on against [[Borussia Dortmund]] and scored two goals in a 5\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2009-10/5/938068/spielanalyse_borussia-dortmund-17_bayern-muenchen-14.html|title=Ribery dankt es van Gaal|work=kicker|date=23 June 2011|accessdate=31 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=Ribery is grateful to Van Gaal}}</ref> Three days later, he scored another [[2 (number)#In other fields|brace]] in a 3\u20130 [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] victory over [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/sep/16/champions-league-round-up-juventus-milan-bayern|title=Filippo Inzaghi double gives Milan the edge over Marseille| work = The Guardian |date=15 September 2009|accessdate=23 June 2011}}</ref> He rounded off September by being named the Bundesliga Player of the Month<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/artikel/307466/|title=Ein kleiner Trost: Mit dem 3. Titel ans Kap|publisher=kicker|accessdate=7 September 2011|date=27 May 2010|language=German|trans-title=A small consolation: to the Cape with a third title}}</ref> and earned praise from his namesake, legendary former Bayern and [[Germany national football team|Germany]] striker [[Gerd M\u00fcller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/news/newsid=1109280/index.html|title=Muller slams Germany forwards|publisher=[[FIFA]]|date=29 September 2009|accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref> After the Haifa match, M\u00fcller was in the starting XI for almost every match,<ref name=\"soccernet\">{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/123465/thomas-muller?cc=5739|title=Thomas M\u00fcller|accessdate=7 September 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> only missing one match, a Champions League match against [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], for which he was suspended,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/chleague/spielrunde/champions-league/2009-10/4/988041/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_girondins-bordeaux-974.html|title=Gourcuff bringt die Bayern an den Abgrund|work=kicker|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=23 June 2011|language=German|trans-title=Gourcuff brings Bayern towards the abyss}}</ref> because he was sent off in an earlier match against the same team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/chleague/spielrunde/champions-league/2009-10/3/988036/spielanalyse_girondins-bordeaux-974_bayern-muenchen-14.html|title=Bayern unterliegen im Kuriosit\u00e4tenkabinett|language=German|work=kicker|date=21 October 2009|accessdate=23 June 2011|trans-title=Bayern lose in curious match}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, M\u00fcller signed a new contract with Bayern Munich through 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1445430.html|title=Van Buyten commits future to Bayern|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=5 February 2010|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref> During the second half of the season, M\u00fcller continued to be a regular first-team starter,<ref name=\"fussballdaten0910\"/> usually playing in a central striking role due to the availability of other [[Winger (soccer)|wide players]] [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]] and [[Arjen Robben]]. In April 2010, he scored the second goal in a 2\u20131 win against title rivals [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/apr/05/bayern-munich-schalke|title=Self-congratulatory Bayern Munich reclaim top spot| work = The Guardian | first = Raphael | last = Honigstein | authorlink = Raphael Honigstein |date=3 April 2010|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref> and in the penultimate league match of the season, he scored the first [[hat-trick]] of his career,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/23303.php|title=M\u00fcller to keep on dreaming|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=2 May 2010|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> in a 3\u20131 win over [[VfL Bochum]] which effectively secured the [[List of German football champions|German title]] for Bayern.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/may/03/schalke-bundesliga-runners-up|title=Schalke find something beautiful in being second best| work = The Guardian | first = Raphael | last = Honigstein | authorlink = Raphael Honigstein|date=1 May 2010|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref> The title was confirmed a week later with a 3\u20131 win at [[Hertha BSC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/may/10/bundesliga-finale-bayern-munich|title=Two-day parties, tears, fights and farewells mark Bundesliga finale| work = The Guardian | first = Raphael | last = Honigstein | authorlink = Raphael Honigstein|date=10 May 2010|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"champions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/matchreport/2010/23368.php|title=Champions Munich finish with a flourish|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=8 May 2010|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> a match which M\u00fcller started.\n\nFor the season, he played in all 34 Bundesliga matches,<ref name=\"2009\u201310 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2009-10/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref> starting 29, and recorded 13 goals and 11 assists.<ref name=\"fussballdaten0910\" /> Bayern and M\u00fcller were back in [[Berlin]] the following week, to face [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in the [[2010 DFB-Pokal Final|final]] of the [[DFB-Pokal]]. M\u00fcller started the match and Bayern won 4\u20130 to complete the domestic [[Double (association football)|double]].<ref name=\"2010cupfinal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2009-10/6/1000000/spielanalyse_werder-bremen-4_bayern-muenchen-14.html|title=Erneute Bayern-Party in Berlin|work=kicker|date=15 May 2010|accessdate=24 June 2011|language=German|trans-title=Another Bayern party in Berlin}}</ref> M\u00fcller scored four goals and made two [[Assist (football)|assists]] during the competition, which made him its leading scorer for [[2009\u201310 DFB-Pokal|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/dfb/2010/statistik/#Tore|title=Torj\u00e4ger des DFB-Pokals 2009/2010|publisher=fussballdaten.de|language=German|date=15 May 2010|accessdate=15 May 2010|trans-title=Top goalscorers of the German cup 2009\u201310}}</ref> Bayern's season ended in pursuit of a first [[Treble (association football)|treble]], in the [[2010 UEFA Champions League Final|2010 Champions League Final]] against [[Inter Milan]] at [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] in Madrid. It was not to be, however, as they lost 2\u20130, with both goals coming from [[Diego Milito]]. M\u00fcller was in the starting line-up and had a key chance just after half-time, with Bayern 1\u20130 down, but his shot was saved by [[J\u00falio C\u00e9sar (football goalkeeper, born 1979)|J\u00falio C\u00e9sar]].<ref name=\"CLfinal2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/22/inter-champions-league-final-bayern|title=Inter win Champions League final as Diego Milito downs Bayern Munich| work = The Guardian |date=22 May 2010|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref> M\u00fcller felt particularly disappointed by this defeat,<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> but he ended his first season as a first-team player with 52 matches played and 19 goals in all competitions.<ref name=\"fussballdaten0910\" />\n\nIn a poll conducted by the sports magazine [[Kicker (sports magazine)|''kicker'']], he was voted by his fellow professionals as the best newcomer of the 2009\u201310 season<ref name=\"newcomer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/de/aktuell/news/2010/23660.php|title=M\u00fcller ist 'Aufsteiger der Saison'|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=31 May 2010|accessdate=1 June 2010|language=German|trans-title=M\u00fcller is newcomer of the year}}</ref> and was named in the Bundesliga [[2009\u201310 Bundesliga#Team of the season|Team of the Season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/24064.php|title=Bayern men dominate 2009\u201310 players\u2019 awards|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=16 July 2010|publisher=Bayern Munich}}</ref> M\u00fcller credits Van Gaal for having had the biggest part to play in his rise to success \u2013 the coach arrived with a reputation for promoting youth team players, particularly at [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], and consistently gave M\u00fcller his chance in the first-team, going as far to say \"''M\u00fcller spielt bei mir immer''\" (\"with me, M\u00fcller will always play\").<ref name=\"immer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abendzeitung-muenchen.de/inhalt.fc-bayern-mueller-spielt-immer-nimmer.36bf05b5-9f65-4592-a123-8f1090078a85.html|title=\"M\u00fcller spielt immer\"? Nimmer!|trans-title=\"M\u00fcller always plays?\" Never!|publisher=Abendzeitung M\u00fcnchen|date=7 November 2010|accessdate=24 August 2011|language=German}}</ref> M\u00fcller, in return, described Van Gaal as \"a genius technician\" who makes players \"improve every time\".<ref name=\"champions1210\" />\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\n{{See also|2010\u201311 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n[[File:Thomas_M\u00fcller_in_Saint-Peterburg,_18_May_2011.png|thumb|upright|right|M\u00fcller with Bayern Munich in Saint Petersburg, Russia, May 2011]]\nM\u00fcller returned from his post-[[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] break to sign another contract extension, this time extending his stay at Bayern until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller extends stay at Bayern until 2015|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/24549.php|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=6 August 2010|accessdate=7 August 2010}}</ref> As with all of Bayern's World Cup participants, he missed much of [[pre-season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/24471.php|title=First pre-season session for World Cup stars|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=7 August 2010}}</ref> and his first match back was the [[2010 DFL-Supercup|Supercup]] against Schalke 04 on 7 August.<ref name=\"WM-Helden M\u00fcller und Klose treffen\">{{cite news|title=WM-Helden M\u00fcller und Klose treffen|url=http://www.kicker.de/d-supercup-fb-1/2010/1/1003714/spielbericht_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-schalke-04-2.html|accessdate=21 February 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=7 August 2010|language=German}}</ref> He was named in the starting 11, and scored the opening goal in a 2\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/2009/index.php?f=0000159886.php|title=Bayern holen den ersten Titel |publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|language=German|date=7 August 2010|accessdate=29 July 2011|trans-title=Bayern take the first title}}</ref> Two weeks later he scored the opening goal of Bayern's [[2010\u201311 FC Bayern Munich season|league season]] in a 2\u20131 home win against [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/1/1013222/spielbericht_bayern-muenchen-14_vfl-wolfsburg-24.html|title=Schweinsteiger der Matchwinner zum Auftakt|work=kicker|language=German|date=20 August 2010|accessdate=20 August 2010|trans-title=Schweinsteiger the match-winner from the start}}</ref> M\u00fcller played in every match of the first half of the season, usually as a starter,<ref name=\"fussballdaten1011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/2011/ |publisher=fussballdaten.de | language = German |title=Spiele von Thomas M\u00fcller in 2010/2011 |accessdate= 1 November 2014}}</ref> but as the team struggled for results, M\u00fcller was unable to match the previous season's goalscoring exploits,<ref name=\"fussballdaten1011\" /> being dropped to the bench,<ref name=\"immer\" /> and even receiving a telling off from Louis van Gaal after missing an easy chance in a 2\u20130 defeat against [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]] in August.<ref name=\"champions1210\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/2/1013255/spielanalyse_1-fc-kaiserslautern-37_bayern-muenchen-14.html|title=1. FC Kaiserslautern \u2013 Bayern M\u00fcnchen 2:0, 1. Bundesliga, Saison 2010/11, 2.Spieltag \u2013 Spielanalyse|language=German|date=27 August 2010|accessdate=1 January 2011|work=kicker|trans-title=1. FC Kaiserslautern 2\u20130 Bayern M\u00fcnchen, Bundesliga season 2010\u201311, matchday 2 \u2013 match report}}</ref> He was philosophical about this dip in form, though,<ref name=\"2010review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/27350.php|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=28 December 2010|accessdate=1 January 2011|title=M\u00fcller\u2019s marvellous year}}</ref> and after eight league games without a goal, he scored in a 4\u20131 win against [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] on 27 November;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/14/1013356/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_eintracht-frankfurt-32.html|title=M\u00fcller nutzt Nikolovs Patzer|accessdate=29 July 2011|date=27 November 2010|work=kicker|language=German|trans-title=M\u00fcller takes advantage of Nikolov's blunder}}</ref> He followed that by scoring in consecutive league and cup wins against [[VfB Stuttgart]] three weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/17/1013386/spielanalyse_vfb-stuttgart-11_bayern-muenchen-14.html|work=kicker|title=Gomez und M\u00fcller als kongeniales Duo|date=19 December 2010|accessdate=29 July 2011|language=German|trans-title=Gomez and M\u00fcller \u2013 A Symbiotic Partnership}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2010-11/3/1123293/spielanalyse_vfb-stuttgart-11_bayern-muenchen-14.html|work=kicker|title=Rasse, Klasse und erneut Tore satt in Stuttgart|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=29 July 2011|language=German|trans-title=Pace, class and more goals in a packed game in Stuttgart}}</ref> These goals took his tally to eight goals in all competitions<ref name=\"fussballdaten1011\" /> and included a spectacular goal to open the scoring in a 2\u20130 Champions League victory against [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on 15 September.<ref name=\"champions1210\">{{cite journal|journal=Champions Magazine|date=December 2010|issue=44|pages=26\u201329|title=The M\u00fcller's tale|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/news/2010/25411.php|title=Van Gaal thrilled by M\u00fcller\u2019s textbook strike|publisher=Bayern Munich|accessdate=19 December 2010|date=16 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs his team was on its winter break, M\u00fcller was left to reflect on what he described as \"an almost unbelievable first year as a pro\".<ref name=\"2010review\" /> M\u00fcller began the second half of the season in good form, but was involved in an altercation with teammate [[Arjen Robben]], who was angered when M\u00fcller showed his displeasure at a poor free-kick Robben took during a 3\u20131 win at Werder Bremen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/873168/arjen-robben-hits-out-at-thomas-muller-following-bayern-row?cc=5739|title=Robben hits out at Muller|publisher=[[ESPN Soccernet]]|date=30 January 2011|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> M\u00fcller again played in every game of the season<ref name=\"2010\u201311 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2010-11/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref> and scored 19 goals (12 in the league),<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espnfc.com/player/123465/thomas-muller?season | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = ESPN FC | accessdate = 20 June 2014}}</ref> but the season was less successful for Bayern, as they finished third in the league,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/spieltag.html|title=1. Bundesliga: Spielpaarungen, Tabelle und Ergebnisse der Saison 2010/11 am 34. Spieltag|work=kicker|date=14 May 2011|accessdate=18 May 2011|language=German|trans-title=Bundesliga: fixtures, table and results of the 2010\u201311 season on the 34th matchday}}</ref> and were knocked out of the [[DFB-Pokal]] in the semi-finals by Schalke 04<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2010-11/5/1129750/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-schalke-04-2.html|title=Raul trifft einmal, Neuer h\u00e4lt alles \u2013 Bayern k.o.|work=kicker|language=German|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=18 May 2011|trans-title=One goal from Raul, and Neuer unbeatable: Bayern are knocked out}}</ref> and in the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]] by Inter Milan; Bayern had won 1\u20130 at the [[San Siro]], and M\u00fcller scored 31 minutes into the second leg to make it 3\u20131 on aggregate, but Inter levelled the score at 3\u20133 in the 88th minute to go through on the [[away goals rule]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/mar/15/bayern-munich-internazionale-champions-league|title=Goran Pandev strikes late as Inter leave Bayern Munich devastated again|accessdate=18 May 2011|date=15 March 2011| work = The Guardian |author=Nesha Starcevic}}</ref> M\u00fcller's mentor Van Gaal was increasingly criticised for inflexibility in tactical, transfer and selection policy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/raphael_honigstein/04/14/vangaal.bayern/index.html|title=Van Gaal's failings were many | first = Raphael | last = Honigstein | authorlink = Raphael Honigstein |date=14 April 2011|accessdate=28 August 2011|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> and ultimately lost his job, being replaced with [[Jupp Heynckes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/apr/10/louis-van-gaal-bayern-munich|title=Louis van Gaal sacked by Bayern Munich| work = The Guardian |accessdate=18 May 2011|date=10 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\n{{See also|2011\u201312 FC Bayern Munich season}}\nIn Bayern's first [[2011\u201312 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] game M\u00fcller was awarded the man of the match after earning two penalties which were converted by [[Mario G\u00f3mez]] and Bastian Schweinsteiger, M\u00fcller then added a third in the closing stages to secure a 3\u20130 victory over [[Eintracht Braunschweig]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2011-12/1/1140230/spielbericht_eintracht-braunschweig-41_bayern-muenchen-14.html | title = M\u00fcller bestraft Braunschweiger Ungeschicktheit | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate =4 January 2012 | date = 1 August 2011}}</ref> It took M\u00fcller five matches for him to get his first league goal; he scored it against Schalke 04 in Bayern's 2\u20130 win. M\u00fcller then scored in Bayern's next home game in the early stages of the match, which they went on to win, 3\u20130. On 26 November 2011, M\u00fcller netted the opener on the half-hour in Bayern's 6\u20130 thrashing of [[FC Ingolstadt 04|FC Ingolstadt]], giving him his second DFB-Pokal goal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2011-12/2/1260356/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-ingolstadt-04-7659.html | title = Pechvogel Pisot \u00f6ffnet den Bayern das Tor | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate =4 January 2012 | date = 26 November 2011}}</ref> M\u00fcller was on the short-list of this year's [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]] award.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/ballondor/media/newsid=1535258/index.html | title = Men\u2019s shortlists for FIFA Ballon d\u2019Or Gala 2011 revealed | publisher = FIFA.com | accessdate =4 January 2012 | date = 1 November 2011}}</ref> On 10 and 15 January, in Bayern's warm up friendlies, M\u00fcller scored three goals in two games, a brace against the [[India national football team|India national team]] (which Bayern then went on to win 4\u20130)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/matchreport/2012/33006.php?fcb_sid=5212e2fd9b807008ab856a15fe2d41b9 | title = Brace for M\u00fcller as FCB ease past India | publisher = FC Bayern Munich | accessdate =16 January 2012 | date = 10 January 2012}}</ref> and one goal in Bayern's other 4\u20130 victory over [[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt|Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/matchreport/2012/33051.php | title = FCB ease past Erfurt in perfect final warm-up | publisher = FC Bayern Munich | accessdate =16 January 2012 | date = 15 January 2012}}</ref> M\u00fcller provided two assists in Bayern's win over VfB Stuttgart in the [[2011\u201312 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]]. On 11 February, Bayern played 1. FC Kaiserslautern and M\u00fcller ended a goal drought lasting since 24 September 2011 with a header in their 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.merkur-online.de/sport/fc-bayern/spassvogel-mueller-war-selbst-ueberrascht-1597961.html | title = M\u00fcller: Erst Torsch\u00fctze, dann Spa\u00dfvogel | publisher = merkur-online.de | accessdate =17 February 2012 | date = 12 February 2012 | language = German}}</ref> On 31 March 2012, M\u00fcller played his 100th [[Bundesliga|Bundesliga game]] against [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/de/aktuell/news/2012/34226.php | title = Lahm und M\u00fcller jubilieren | trans-title = Lahm and M\u00fcller celebrate | language = German |date=31 March 2012 |publisher=FC Bayern Munich | accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bundesliga.de/en/liga/clubs/fc-bayern-muenchen/index.php?firsttab=kader&player=37903 |title = Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = Bundesliga |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref> On 19 May 2012, M\u00fcller scored the opening goal in the Champions League final against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] with a powerful header. He was substituted shortly afterwards. Bayern Munich, however, lost the final on penalties. M\u00fcller stated how dissatisfied he was about the amount of time he had spent on the bench recently.<ref name=Muellerdissatisfied>{{cite news|title=Teams alerted as Muller reveals Bayern anger|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/154396.html|accessdate=9 June 2012|newspaper=[[ESPN (UK)]]|date=8 June 2012}}</ref> M\u00fcller said that although he was dissatisfied he wanted to stay at Bayern.<ref name=Muellerdissatisfied/> During the season, M\u00fcller scored seven goals in 34 league matches, two goals in five German Cup matches, and two goals in 14 Champions League matches.<ref name=\"2011\u201312 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2011-12/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\n{{See also|2012\u201313 FC Bayern Munich season}}\nM\u00fcller's first [[2012\u201313 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] goal of the season came over [[2011\u201312 2. Bundesliga|2. Bundesliga]] champions [[SpVgg Greuther F\u00fcrth]] in Bayern's 3\u20130 victory on 27 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2012/0000220346.php |title=Bayern can 'only get better' |publisher=Bundesliga |date=27 August 2012 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607005927/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2012/0000220346.php |archivedate=7 June 2014}}</ref> On 2 September, he netted a brace as Bayern thrashed southern rivals VfB Stuttgart, 6\u20131, in front of 71,000 at the newly expanded [[Allianz Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bundesligafanatic.com/bayern-munchen-6-1-stuttgart-heynckes-team-again-dominant/ |title=Bayern M\u00fcnchen 6 \u2013 1 Stuttgart \u2013 Heynckes\u2019 Team Again Dominant |publisher=Bundesliga Fanatic |date=2 September 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012 | first = Gerry | last = Wittmann}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2012/0000221282.php |title=Bayern hit Stuttgart for six |publisher=Bundesliga |date=2 September 2012 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |first=Christopher |last=Mayer-Lodge |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607005810/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2012/0000221282.php |archivedate=7 June 2014}}</ref> M\u00fcller helped Bayern achieve a record-breaking start to the league season, when he netted a brace over newly promoted [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]] on 20 October in their 5\u20130 victory, recording Bayern's eighth successive win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=346334&cc=5901 |title=Bayern continue perfect start |publisher=ESPN FC |date=20 October 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012}}</ref> Three days later, he scored his first [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal of the season, netting from the penalty spot, as Bayern defeated [[Lille OSC|Lille]] 1\u20130 at the French side's newly built [[Grand Stade Lille M\u00e9tropole]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/matches/round=2000347/match=2009531/postmatch/report/index.html#bayern+overcome+losc |title=M\u00fcller spot kick secures victory for Bayern |publisher=UEFA |date=23 October 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012 | first = Chris | last = Burke}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 December, after his good run of form in the first half of the Bundesliga season, M\u00fcller pledged his allegiance claiming he was at home in Munich and that, \"There is no club to step up from when you leave FC Bayern... there almost is no better club.\"<ref name=\"Pinnacle\">{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1261967/thomas-muller:-bayern-munich-the-pinnacle?cc=5901 |title=Muller: Bayern the pinnacle |publisher=ESPN FC |date=13 December 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012 | first = Stephan | last = Uersfeld}}</ref> Six days later, he signed a two-year contract extension, keeping him at the Allianz Arena until 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1270008/thomas-muller-inks-new-deal-at-bayern-munich?cc=5901 |title=Muller inks new deal at Bayern |publisher=ESPN FC |date=19 December 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012 | first = Stephan | last = Uersfeld}}</ref> At the winter break in the Bundesliga, he had nine goals and seven assists in 16 league appearances and a further three goals in the Champions League;<ref name=\"Pinnacle\" /> this gave him a total of 13 goals halfway through the season, including his strike against Borussia Dortmund in Bayern's win in the [[2012 DFL-Supercup]]. M\u00fcller scored his first goal in Bayern's second game back from the break in a 2\u20130 away win over VfB Stuttgart. M\u00fcller tapped in his fifth goal of the Champions League campaign on 2 April, completing a 2\u20130 first leg defeat of [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the quarter-finals, ending the Italian club's 18-match unbeaten record in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/matches/round=2000349/match=2009603/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Bayern take command against Juventus |publisher=UEFA |date=2 April 2013 | accessdate=2 April 2013 | first = Andy | last = James}}</ref> On 23 April 2013, M\u00fcller scored two goals and gave one assist in 4\u20130 win against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the Champions League semi-final in the Allianz Arena.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2313719/Bayern-Munich-4-Barcelona-0--Match-report-Thomas-Muller-Mario-Gomez-Arjen-Robben-Bundesliga-advantage.html|title= Bayern Munich 4 Barcelona 0: Muller brace seals comfortable win as Messi and Co face uphill task to make Wembley final|date=23 April 2013|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref> On the return fixture, M\u00fcller scored a header as Bayern won 3\u20130 and gave Barcelona their biggest defeat ever in the Champions League, with a 7\u20130 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/matches/round=2000350/match=2009610/postmatch/report/index.html | title = Clinical Bayern complete Barcelona conquest | publisher = UEFA.com | date = 1 May 2013 | accessdate = 7 June 2013 | first = Graham | last = Hunter}}</ref> M\u00fcller then went on to play an important role in Bayern's 2\u20131 victory over Borussia Dortmund in the [[2013 UEFA Champions League Final|final]]. On 1 June, M\u00fcller scored a penalty in the final of the [[2012\u201313 DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/en/match/106533/fc-bayern-m%C3%BCnchen-vs-vfb-stuttgart/report?ICID=OP | title = Bayern Munich 3\u20132 Stuttgart: Gomez at the double as Bavarians survive Schwaben fightback to complete treble | publisher = goal.com | date = 1 June 2013 | accessdate = 7 June 2013 | first = Enis | last = Koylu}}</ref> Bayern won the cup 3\u20132 to complete an historic treble. M\u00fcller scored 23 goals overall in the season (including all competitions), netting 13 in the Bundesliga,<ref name=\"2012\u201313 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2012-13/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate=21 February 2014|language=German}}</ref> one in the Pokal,<ref name=\"2012\u201313 season\"/> and an impressive eight in the Champions League,<ref name=\"2012\u201313 season\"/> he also added one in the [[2012 DFL-Supercup]] which Bayern won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/en/people/germany/21854/thomas-m%C3%BCller?ICID=OP | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = goal.com | accessdate = 7 June 2013}}</ref> This topped off M\u00fcller's highest scoring season to date.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://espnfc.com/player/_/id/123465/thomas-m%C3%BCller?cc=5739# | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = ESPN FC | accessdate = 7 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n{{See also|2013\u201314 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n[[File:Thomas M\u00fcller 2013.jpg|thumb|right|upright|M\u00fcller playing for Bayern in 2013]]\nM\u00fcller began the [[2013\u201314 FC Bayern Munich season|2013\u201314 season]] by playing in the German Super Cup. by scoring in seven of Bayern's 12 pre-season games. His first competitive match came against Borussia Dortmund in the German Super Cup.<ref name=\"Reus er\u00f6ffnet und beendet den Torreigen\">{{cite news|title=Reus er\u00f6ffnet und beendet den Torreigen|url=http://www.kicker.de/d-supercup-fb-1/2013/1/1887827/spielbericht_borussia-dortmund-17_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=21 February 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=27 July 2013|language=German}}</ref> On 5 August, M\u00fcller scored a hat-trick as Bayern won 5\u20130 in the team's [[2013\u201314 DFB-Pokal]] first-round game against [[BSV Schwarz-Wei\u00df Rehden|Schwarz-Wei\u00df Rehden]]. In Bayern's opening [[2013\u201314 Bundesliga]] fixture, M\u00fcller missed a penalty for the first time. Seconds later, the save from the penalty flicked the hand of [[\u00c1lvaro Dom\u00ednguez (footballer, born 1989)|\u00c1lvaro Dom\u00ednguez]] which resulted in another penalty which [[David Alaba]] converted. After this, M\u00fcller stated, \"I am still happy to take penalties, but I think David Alaba is the main man for spot kicks for now.\" He played in the [[2013 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]].<ref name=\"Neuer h\u00e4lt den Supercup fest\">{{cite news|title=Neuer h\u00e4lt den Supercup fest|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/intwettbewerbe/uefa-supercup/2013/1/1887586/spielbericht_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-chelsea-505.html|accessdate=21 February 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=30 August 2013|language=German}}</ref> On 25 September, against [[Hannover 96]] in the second round of the DFB-Pokal, M\u00fcller scored twice taking his cup tally to five goals in just two games. On 28 September, M\u00fcller scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 victory over VfL Wolfsburg, giving him his first goal in the [[2013\u201314 Bundesliga]]. M\u00fcller scored his first [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League]] goal of the campaign and Bayern defeated [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 3\u20131 at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]] on 2 October. He played in a match at the [[2013 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]].<ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\">{{cite web|title=Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/thomas-mueller/2/|publisher=World Football|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2014, M\u00fcller scored Bayern's second goal in a 2\u20130 extra-time defeat of Borussia Dortmund in the [[2014 DFB-Pokal Final]], giving ''die Roten'' the tenth league and cup [[Double (association football)|double]] in their history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2014/05/17/bayern-beats-dortmund-2-0-in-german-cup-final/9221529/|title=Bayern beats Dortmund 2\u20130 in German Cup final|date=17 May 2014|accessdate=18 May 2014|work=USA Today}}</ref> M\u00fcller finished as the tournament's top scorer with eight goals in five appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/de/d-dfb-pokal/die-statistiken-zum-dfb-pokalfinale-2014/58477.html|title=Die Statistiken zum DFB-Pokalfinale 2014|date=18 May 2014|accessdate=18 May 2014|language=German|work=Deutscher Fu\u00dfball-Bund}}</ref> He finished the season by scoring 13 goals in 31 league matches, eight goals in five DFB-Pokal matches, and five goals in 12 Champions League matches.<ref name=\"2013\u201314 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2013-14/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html|publisher=kicker|accessdate= 17 May 2014|language=German}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n{{See also|2014\u201315 FC Bayern Munich season}}\nAfter the [[2013\u201314 FC Bayern Munich season|2013\u201314 season]], M\u00fcller signed a new contract keeping him at Bayern until 2019<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayern Munich: Philipp Lahm and Thomas Muller sign new deals|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27793926|accessdate=11 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=11 June 2014}}</ref> and rejected a contract offer from [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref name=\"Muller claims he turned down 'astronomical' Man United offer\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Mueller: I rejected more money at United|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/335261.html|accessdate=20 August 2014|publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]]|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> M\u00fcller played in the [[2014 DFL-Supercup|DFL-Supercup]],<ref name=\"2014supercup\">{{cite news|title=Aubameyang k\u00f6pft BVB zum Supercup-Sieg|url=http://www.kicker.de/d-supercup-fb-1/2014/1/2396815/spielbericht_borussia-dortmund-17_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=13 August 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=13 August 2014|language=German}}</ref> which was Bayern's first match in the [[2014\u201315 FC Bayern Munich season|2014\u201315 season]]. Bayern lost the match 2\u20130.<ref name=\"2014supercup\"/> His first goal of the season was against [[SC Preu\u00dfen M\u00fcnster|Preu\u00dfen M\u00fcnster]] in the [[2014\u201315 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] on 17 August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=G\u00f6tze, M\u00fcller, Alaba und Pizarro \u2013 FCB auf Kurs|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2014-15/1/2397917/spielbericht_preussen-muenster-104_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=17 August 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=17 August 2014|language=German}}</ref> Then in the opening match of the Bundesliga,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dunbar|first1=Ross|title=Bayern to open season against Wolfsburg as Bundesliga fixtures confirmed|url=http://www.dw.de/bayern-to-open-season-against-wolfsburg-as-bundesliga-fixtures-confirmed/a-17733107|accessdate=23 August 2014|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=24 June 2014}}</ref> on 22 August 2014,<ref name=\"Robben macht's besser als Malanda\">{{cite news|title=Robben macht's besser als Malanda|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2014-15/1/2407218/spielbericht_bayern-muenchen-14_vfl-wolfsburg-24.html|accessdate=23 August 2014|newspaper=kicker|date=22 August 2014|language=German}}</ref> M\u00fcller scored the opening goal of Bayern's Bundesliga season against VfL Wolfsburg.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayern m\u00fchen sich zum Erfolg gegen Wolfsburg|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/fc-bayern-muenchen/article131507396/Bayern-muehen-sich-zum-Erfolg-gegen-Wolfsburg.html|accessdate=23 August 2014|publisher=Die Welt|date=22 August 2014|language=German}}</ref> Bayern went on to win the match 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Robben macht's besser als Malanda\"/> On 11 March 2015, M\u00fcller scored two goals against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] in a 7\u20130 win<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Bayern d\u00fcst ins Viertelfinale|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/champions-league-fc-bayern-duest-ins-viertelfinale-1.2389807|accessdate=12 March 2015|publisher=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|date=11 March 2015|language=German}}</ref> to draw level with former teammate Mario G\u00f3mez as the top-scoring German player in UEFA Champions League history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com.au/bayern-munich/story/2343584/bayern-munichs-thomas-muller----you-wish-for-a-match-like-that|title=Bayern Munich's Thomas Muller: You wish for a match like that|accessdate=13 March 2015|work=ESPN}}</ref> He subsequently became the leader when he scored in a 6\u20131 win against Porto on 21 April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=Starcevic|first=Nesha|title=Bayern routs Porto reach Champions semis|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2015/04/21/bayern-routs-porto-reach-champions-semis.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|agency=The Associated Press|publisher=Toronto Star|date=21 April 2015}}</ref> He finished the season with 13 goals in 32 league matches, a goal in five DFB-Pokal matches, and seven goals in ten Champions League matches.<ref name=\"2014\u201315 season\">{{cite web|title=M\u00fcller, Thomas|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2014-15/bayern-muenchen-14/39317/spieler_thomas-mueller.html | publisher = kicker | accessdate = 16 May 2015 | language = German}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\n{{See also|2015\u201316 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n[[File:Thomas Mueller Training FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen-5.jpg|thumb|upright|right|M\u00fcller at training session in 2015]]\nM\u00fcller started the season by playing in the [[2015 DFL-Supercup|DFL-Supercup]] against VfL Wolfsburg.<ref name=\"Joker Bendtner ist zweimal zur Stelle\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/d-supercup-fb-1/2015/1/2841005/spielbericht_vfl-wolfsburg-24_bayern-muenchen-14.html | title = Joker Bendtner ist zweimal zur Stelle | language = de | website = kicker.de | date = 1 August 2015 | access-date = 1 August 2015}}</ref> He started the [[2015\u201316 Bundesliga|league season]] with two goals against Hamburger SV,<ref>{{cite news|title=Doppelpack: Es m\u00fcllert zum Auftakt|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/1/2854915/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_hamburger-sv-12.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=14 August 2015|language=German}}</ref> a goal against [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Lewandowski erweitert seine Serie gegen Baumann|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/2/2854949/spielanalyse_1899-hoffenheim-3209_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=22 August 2015|language=German}}</ref> two goals against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]],<ref name=\"Strahlemann M\u00fcller l\u00e4sst Bayer alt aussehen\">{{cite news|title=Strahlemann M\u00fcller l\u00e4sst Bayer alt aussehen|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/3/2854951/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_bayer-leverkusen-9.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=29 August 2015|language=German}}</ref> and a goal against [[FC Augsburg]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcller bleibt vom Punkt cool\">{{cite news|title=M\u00fcller bleibt vom Punkt cool|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/4/2854960/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-augsburg-91.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=12 September 2015|language=German}}</ref> in the first four matchdays. He had scored from the penalty spot against Bayer Leverkusen<ref name=\"Strahlemann M\u00fcller l\u00e4sst Bayer alt aussehen\"/> and Augsburg.<ref name=\"M\u00fcller bleibt vom Punkt cool\"/> He failed to score in his next three Bundesliga matches.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2015-16/39317/vereinsspieler_thomas-mueller.html | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | language = de | website = kicker.de | access-date = 5 December 2015}}</ref> He failed to convert a penalty shot against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] on matchday seven.<ref name=\"FCB siegt dank Lewandowski im Schongang\">{{cite news|title=FCB siegt dank Lewandowski im Schongang|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/7/2854995/spielanalyse_1-fsv-mainz-05-30_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=28 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=26 September 2015|language=German}}</ref> His next Bundesliga goal came when he scored two goals against Borussia Dortmund on matchday eight.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/> One of the goals was scored from the penalty spot.<ref name=\"Erst M\u00fcller eiskalt, sp\u00e4ter Lewandowski konsequent\">{{cite news|title=Erst M\u00fcller eiskalt, sp\u00e4ter Lewandowski konsequent|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/8/2854996/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_borussia-dortmund-17.html|accessdate=28 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=4 October 2015|language=German}}</ref> His goalscoring continued in other competitions. He scored two goals against Wolfsburg in the second round of the [[2015\u201316 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayern wirft den Titelverteidiger raus \u2013 dank M\u00fcller und Costa|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2015-16/2/3243148/spielanalyse_vfl-wolfsburg-24_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=27 October 2015}}</ref> and in Champions League, two goals against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Doppelter M\u00fcller bringt den FC Bayern auf Kurs|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/chleague/spielrunde/champions-league/2015-16/1/3254880/spielanalyse_olympiakos-piraeus_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=kicker|date=16 September 2015|language=German}}</ref> two goals against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Magowan|first1=Alistair|title=Bayern Mun 5 1 Arsenal|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34675853|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> and a goal in the return leg against Olympiacos.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Matar|first1=Daniella|title=Barcelona, Bayern Munich advance in Champions League|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2015/11/24/barcelona-bayern-munich-advance-in-champions-league.html|accessdate=25 November 2015|agency=The Associated Press|publisher=Toronto Star|date=24 November 2015}}</ref> In scoring in the home win over Olympiacos, M\u00fcller became the youngest player to win 50 UEFA Champions League games, beating the record of [[Lionel Messi]] by 14 months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2310014.html|title=This season's Champions League record-breakers|date=12 December 2015|work=UEFA}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2015, M\u00fcller came on as a 46th-minute substitute for Franck Rib\u00e9ry in a 2\u20130 win against [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Doppelschlag Lewandowski: F\u00fcnfter Bayern-Sieg|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/chleague/spielrunde/champions-league/2015-16/6/3254883/spielanalyse_dinamo-zagreb_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=10 December 2015|publisher=kicker|date=9 December 2015|language=German}}</ref> He failed to convert his penalty shot in the match<ref>{{cite news|title=Robert Lewandowski helps Bayern Munich ease past Dinamo Zagreb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/09/dinamo-zagreb-bayern-munich-champions-league-match-report|accessdate=10 December 2015|agency=Reuters|publisher=The Guardian|date=9 December 2015}}</ref> and finished the group stage with five goals from six appearances.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/> On 18 December 2015, M\u00fcller signed a new contract with Bayern, keeping him at the club until 2021.<ref>{{cite news|title=Der FC Bayern verl\u00e4ngert mit vier Superstars|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article150112292/Der-FC-Bayern-verlaengert-mit-vier-Superstars.html|accessdate=21 December 2015|publisher=Die Welt|date=18 December 2015|language=German}}</ref> On 19 December 2015,<ref name=\"Minimalistische M\u00fcnchner siegen dank M\u00fcllers Elfmeter\">{{cite news|title=Minimalistische M\u00fcnchner siegen dank M\u00fcllers Elfmeter|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/17/2855083/spielbericht_hannover-96-58_bayern-muenchen-14.html|accessdate=21 December 2015|publisher=kicker|date=19 December 2015|language=German}}</ref> Bayern defeated Hannover 96 1\u20130<ref name=\"Minimalistische M\u00fcnchner siegen dank M\u00fcllers Elfmeter\"/> with a goal from the penalty mark from M\u00fcller.<ref name=\"Bayern Munich\u2019s win at Hannover overshadowed by Guardiola speculation\">{{cite news|title=Bayern Munich\u2019s win at Hannover overshadowed by Guardiola speculation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/19/hannover-bayern-munich-bundesliga-match-report|accessdate=22 December 2015|agency=Reuters|publisher=The Guardian|date=19 December 2015}}</ref> Bayern went on winter break after the match.<ref name=\"Bayern Munich\u2019s win at Hannover overshadowed by Guardiola speculation\"/> M\u00fcller finished the first half of the league with 14 goals from 17 appearances.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/> This includes scoring five goals from the penalty mark in six opportunities.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/> He had scored 21 goals in 25 appearances in all competitions up until the winter break.<ref name=\"Joker Bendtner ist zweimal zur Stelle\"/><ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/>\n\nOn 12 March 2016, M\u00fcller scored a brace in a 5\u20130 victory over Werder Bremen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/12/bayern-munich-werder-bremen-bundesliga-match-report|title=Bayern Munich hit Werder Bremen for five as Thomas M\u00fcller bags brace |date=12 March 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> Four days later, with Bayern trailing Juventus 1\u20132 in the second leg of the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]], he scored a 91st-minute equaliser before Bayern won in extra time 4\u20132 (6\u20134 aggregate).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35814918|title=Bayern Munich 4\u20132 Juventus|date=16 March 2016|publisher=BBC Sport|last =Lewis|first =Aimee|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 2016, M\u00fcller scored both goals in Bayern's 2\u20130 defeat of Werder Bremen in the DFB-Pokal semi-final. His first goal of the match was his 150th for the club in all competitions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport1.de/fussball/dfb-pokal/2016/04/dfb-pokal-fc-bayern-muenchen-gegen-werder-bremen-in-der-datenanalyse|title=Daten: M\u00fcller zieht an Hoene\u00df vorbei|language=German|date=20 April 2016|work=Sport1 | access-date = 22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2016, M\u00fcller had a penalty kick saved by [[Jan Oblak]] in the Champions League semi-final second leg at home to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]. The match ended in a 2\u20131 win for Bayern but the team was knocked out on the [[away goals rule]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/05/03/bayern-munich-2-atletico-madrid-1-pep-guardiola-pays-heavy-penal/|title=Bayern 2 Atletico 1: Guardiola pays heavy penalty for Muller miss as Atleti reach final on away goals|date=3 May 2016|work=The Telegraph | access-date = 4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe finished the season by scoring 20 goals in 31 league matches, four goals in five German Cup matches, and eight goals in 12 Champions League matches.<ref name=\"2015\u201316 season\"/> He didn't score in the German Super Cup.<ref name=\"Joker Bendtner ist zweimal zur Stelle\"/>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n{{See also|2016\u201317 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n\nM\u00fcller started the season by winning and scoring in the [[2016 DFL-Supercup|2016 German Super Cup]] against Borussia Dortmund on 14 August 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayern Munich 2\u20130 Borussia Dortmund: Carlo Ancelotti wins first German trophy|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37079772|accessdate=14 August 2016|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2016}}</ref> In the league, M\u00fcller did not score for 999 minutes until he scored during a home game against [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in the 76th minute.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fourfourtwo.com.au/news/bayern-munich-5-wolfsburg-0-muller-breaks-duck-as-hosts-go-top-444272 | title = Bayern Munich 5 Wolfsburg 0: Muller breaks duck as hosts go top | website = FourFourTwo | date = 10 December 2016 | access-date = 10 December 2016}}</ref> He finished the [[2016\u201317 FC Bayern Munich season|2016\u201317 season]] by scoring five goals in 29 [[2016\u201317 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] appearances, no goals in three German Cup appearances, and three goals in nine [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] appearances.<ref name=\"2016\u201317 season\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2016-17/bayern-muenchen-14/39317/spieler_thomas-mueller.html | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | language = de | website = kicker.de | access-date = 20 May 2017}}</ref> M\u00fcller did have a career best 12 assists in the Bundesliga.\n\nSeveral German football experts like [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]] blamed manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]] for M\u00fcller's struggles in front of the goal. Ancelotti often preferred [[Thiago Alc\u00e2ntara]] as the player playing behind the striker, M\u00fcller's prime position. M\u00fcller was often benched for the important matches in Europe and in the Bundesliga.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2017/8/29/16217850/lothar-matthaus-carlo-ancelotti-thomas-muller | title = Lothar Matth\u00e4us believes Carlo Ancelotti is at fault for Thomas M\u00fcller\u2019s drop off | website = bavarianfootballworks.com | date = 29 August 2017 | access-date = 4 March 2018 | first = Tom | last = Adams}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\n{{See also|2017\u201318 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n\nM\u00fcller started the [[2017\u201318 FC Bayern Munich season|2017\u201318 season]] by playing in the 2017 German Super Cup.<ref name=\"2017 German Super Cup\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/d-supercup-fb-1/2017/1/3813700/spielbericht_borussia-dortmund-17_bayern-muenchen-14.html | title = Bayerns erster Titel dank Flippertor und Ulreich | language = de | website = kicker.de | date = 5 August 2017 | access-date = 5 August 2017}}</ref> He played in the opening 67 minutes before being replaced by [[Kingsley Coman]].<ref name=\"2017 German Super Cup\"/> His first goal of the season was against Mainz on matchday four of the [[2017\u201318 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]].<ref name=\"2017\u201318 season\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2017-18/bayern-muenchen-14/39317/spieler_thomas-mueller.html | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | language = de | website = kicker.de | access-date = 20 February 2018}}</ref> On 21 January 2018, he scored two goals against Werder Bremen in the Bundesliga.<ref>{{cite web|title=4:2! Bremen erweist sich als gro\u00dfe H\u00fcrde|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2017-18/19/3827750/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_werder-bremen-4.html|website=kicker.de|publisher=kicker|accessdate=20 February 2018|language=German}}</ref> On 20 February 2018, M\u00fcller scored two goals against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|title=M\u00fcller spielt den T\u00fcr\u00f6ffner bei Bayerns Gala|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/chleague/spielrunde/champions-league/2017-18/7/4200860/spielbericht_bayern-muenchen-14_besiktas-istanbul.html|accessdate=20 February 2018|publisher=kicker|language=German}}</ref>\n\nM\u00fcller led the Bundesliga with 14 assists. M\u00fcller also scored 8 goals in 29 league matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/lewandowski-thomas-muller-2017-18-most-goals-most-assists-top-stats-481046.jsp | title = Robert Lewandowski, Thomas M\u00fcller and the Bundesliga's 2017/18 chart-toppers | publisher = bundesliga.com | accessdate = 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\n{{See also|2018\u201319 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n\nM\u00fcller started the [[2018\u201319 FC Bayern Munich season|2018\u201319 season]] by starting in the [[2018 DFL-Supercup|German Super Cup]].<ref name=\"2018 German Super Cup\">{{cite web |title=FCB gewinnt Supercup \u2013 Lewandowski macht den Unterschied |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/d-supercup-fb-1/2018/1/4213948/spielanalyse_eintracht-frankfurt-32_bayern-muenchen-14.html |website=kicker.de |publisher=kicker |accessdate=19 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> M\u00fcller scored in the first two matchdays in the [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|Bundesliga season]].<ref name=\"2018\u201319 season\">{{cite web |title=Thomas M\u00fcller |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2018-19/bayern-muenchen-14/39317/spieler_thomas-mueller.html |website=kicker.de |publisher=kicker |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He scored in the second round of the [[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal|German Cup]] against [[SV R\u00f6dinghausen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wagner schie\u00dft pomadige Bayern ins Achtelfinale |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2018-19/2/4546346/spielanalyse_sv-roedinghausen-20930_bayern-muenchen-14.html |website=kicker.de |publisher=kicker |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He scored two goals against [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]] in the Bundesliga on 24 November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=90.+3! Lukebakio schockt die Bayern mit Tor drei |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2018-19/12/4243364/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_fortuna-duesseldorf-13.html |website=kicker.de |publisher=kicker |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=German}}</ref> On 12 December 2018, M\u00fcller played his 105th Champions League match in a match against [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] and therefore leveling former club legend [[Philipp Lahm]] as the record appearance holder in the Champions League at Bayern.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-and-ajax-deliver-six-goal-thriller-on-memorable-european-night/a-46705178 | title = Bayern Munich and Ajax deliver six-goal thriller on memorable European night | website = dw.com | date = 12 December 2018 | access-date = 2 January 2019}}</ref> In that same match M\u00fcller was sent off for the first time in his career for a straight red card.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thomas Muller sent off as Robert Lewandowski double sees Bayern claim top spot in Group E |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=526414 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |agency=Reuters |publisher=ESPN |date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ajax 3 3 Bayern |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46543556 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> This resulted in a two-match suspension.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zwei Spiele Sperre f\u00fcr M\u00fcller - Bayern legt Berufung ein |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/thomas-mueller-liverpool-sperre-1.4283938 |accessdate=11 January 2019 |publisher=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung |date=11 January 2019 |language=German}}</ref> On 15 December 2018, M\u00fcller made his 300th Bundesliga appearance for Bayern against Hannover 96.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hannover-bayern-munich-live-line-ups-stats-james-rodriguez-robben-lewandowski-fantasy-518926.jsp | title = Hannover vs Bayern match report | publisher = bundesliga.com | accessdate = 15 December 2018|date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May 2019, M\u00fcller won his seventh consecutive Bundesliga title as Bayern finished two points above Dortmund with 78 points. It was M\u00fcller's eighth Bundesliga title. A week later, M\u00fcller won his fifth [[DFB-Pokal]] as Bayern defeated [[RB Leipzig]] 3-0 in the [[2019 DFB-Pokal Final]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/rb-leipzig-bayern-munich-live-dfb-cup-final-james-rodriguez-lewandowski-neuer-4678 | title = Robert Lewandowski hits brace as Bayern Munich beat RB Leipzig in DFB Cup final to seal the double | publisher = bundesliga.com | accessdate = 27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\n{{See also|2019\u201320 FC Bayern Munich season}}\n\nOn 2 November 2019, M\u00fcller made his 500th competitive appearance for Bayern, becoming the 10th Bayern player to reach this mark since the club's promotion to the Bundesliga in 1965.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2019/11/milestone-for-mueller | title = Milestone for Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = fcbayern.com | accessdate = 10 November 2019}}</ref> The following month, he became the first-ever player to register 11 assists in the first half of a Bundesliga, achieving the new record in his side's 2\u20130 win over Wolfsburg.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/thomas-muller-assist-record-first-half-2019-20-season-bayern-munich-8908|title=Bayern Munich's Thomas M\u00fcller sets new Bundesliga assist record|publisher=Bundesliga|date=23 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Thomas M\u00fcller, Germany national football team (03).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Thomas M\u00fcller wears number 13 for Germany, a number famously worn by German legend [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] who said of his namesake; \"he's going to be a great player\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://m.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=gerd-muller-thomas-will-break-records-2375765.html | title = Gerd Muller: Thomas will break records | publisher = FIFA.com | date = 18 June 2014 | accessdate = 20 June 2014}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Thomas M\u00fcller, Germany national football team (05).jpg|thumb|upright|right|M\u00fcller with Germany in 2011]]\n[[File:Thomas M\u00fcller, Germany national football team (07).jpg|thumb|right|M\u00fcller in a [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].]]\nM\u00fcller represented [[Germany national youth football team|Germany]] at various youth levels, starting with the under-16s in 2004.<ref name=\"DFBprofile\">{{cite web|url=http://team.dfb.de/de/das-team/sturm/thomas-mueller/biografie/page/1378.html?1267017907|title=Thomas Mueller \u2013 Biografie|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|accessdate=30 June 2010|language=German|trans-title=Thomas M\u00fcller \u2013 Biography|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722042740/http://team.dfb.de/de/das-team/sturm/thomas-mueller/biografie/page/1378.html?1267017907|archivedate=22 July 2010}}</ref> In August 2009, he was called up to the [[Germany national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] for his debut in a 3\u20131 [[friendly match|friendly]] defeat against [[Turkey national under-21 football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/intwettbewerbe/u-21-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2009/1/946103/spielbericht_deutschland-3096_tuerkei-u-21.html|title=T\u00fcrkei vermiest Adrions Deb\u00fct|work=kicker|date=11 August 2009|accessdate=31 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=Turkey spoil Adrion's debut}}</ref> He earned six caps for the under-21s and scored one goal,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=500109&no_cache=1&action=showPlayer&player=mueller_tommy&lang=D&cHash=65825f7f84|title=U 21-Nationalteam M\u00e4nner \u2013 Nationalspieler Thomas M\u00fcller|publisher=[[German Football Association|DFB]]|accessdate=31 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=Under-21 men's national team \u2013 player Thomas M\u00fcller}}</ref> the eighth in an 11\u20130 thrashing of [[San Marino national under-21 football team|San Marino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/index.php?id=501415&spielid=314&action=schema&teama=San%20Marino&teamb=Deutschland|title=San Marino \u2013 Germany 0:11 (0:5)|publisher=[[German Football Association|DFB]]|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=25 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October of the same year, M\u00fcller's regular appearances for Bayern's first team caused [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]] [[Germany national football team manager|manager]] [[Joachim L\u00f6w]] to publicly consider him for a call-up,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/515765/artikel_Loew-bleibt---wenn-alle-bleiben.html|title=L\u00f6w bleibt \u2013 wenn alle bleiben|trans-title=L\u00f6w stays \u2013 if everyone stays|work=kicker|language=German|date=12 October 2009|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/516070/artikel_DFB-Team-trifft-auf-Drogba-26-Co.html|title=DFB-Team trifft auf Drogba & Co.|trans-title=DFB team encounters Drogba & Co.|work=kicker|language=German|date=20 October 2009|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref> despite initial reluctance from the Bayern Munich board;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/wm/karl-heinz-rummenigge-empfiehlt-langen-urlaub-11685094.bild.html|title=Rummenigge empfiehlt langen Urlaub|trans-title=Rummenigge recommends long holiday|publisher=[[Bild]]|language=German|date=3 March 2010|accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref> the following month, M\u00fcller was named in the squad for a friendly against the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/06/aaron-hunt-germany-call-up|title=Aaron Hunt wins Germany call-up after turning back on England| work = The Guardian |date=6 November 2009|accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref> However, this coincided with the death of national team [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Robert Enke]], which led to the cancellation of a match against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] the same week.<ref name=\"callup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/22136.php|title=M\u00fcller proud after call to Germany set-up|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=27 January 2010|accessdate=1 February 2010}}</ref> With less opportunity to try out new players, and with the under-21 team facing crucial [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship qualification|qualifiers]] for the [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|2011 European Championship]], L\u00f6w and under-21 manager [[Rainer Adrion]] felt that M\u00fcller was needed at the under-21 level, and M\u00fcller was called back into the under-21s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/517194/artikel_Mueller-hat-Verstaendnis-fuer-Loew.html|title=M\u00fcller hat Verst\u00e4ndnis f\u00fcr L\u00f6w|work=kicker|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=31 January 2010|language=German|trans-title=M\u00fcller understands L\u00f6w}}</ref>\n\nHe was back in the senior squad for its next get-together, a training session in [[Sindelfingen]] in January 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/519918/artikel_Robert-Huth-ist-wieder-da.html|title=Robert Huth ist wieder da|work=kicker|language=German|date=21 January 2010|accessdate=31 January 2010|trans-title=Robert Huth is back}}</ref> and was named in the squad for the following match, a friendly against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in March.<ref name=\"Argentina-callup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/521561/artikel_DFB-Team-mit-Mueller-und-Kroos.html|title=DFB-Team mit M\u00fcller und Kroos|work=kicker|accessdate=26 February 2010|date=26 February 2010|language=German|trans-title=German national team with M\u00fcller and Kroos}}</ref> He made his debut in this game in the starting XI at the Allianz Arena, his home stadium with Bayern. He was substituted in the 66th minute for fellow debutant [[Toni Kroos]] as Germany lost 1\u20130.<ref name=\"internationaldebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/fussball-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2010/1/993390/spielanalyse_deutschland_argentinien.html|title=L\u00f6w-Elf misslingt der H\u00e4rtetest|date=4 March 2010|accessdate=3 August 2011|work=kicker|language=German|trans-title=L\u00f6w's team fail the acid test}}</ref>\n\n===2010 World Cup===\nM\u00fcller was named in Germany's provisional 27-man [[2010 FIFA World Cup squads#Germany|squad]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] along with seven other Bayern Munich players.<ref name=\"wcprovisional\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/06/germany-world-cup-squad|title=Hans-J\u00f6rg Butt called up to Germany's preliminary World Cup squad| work = The Guardian |date=6 May 2010|accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref> Despite suffering a scare when he fell off his bicycle at the team's training camp in [[South Tyrol]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.t-home.de/en/news/news/2010/23630.php|title=Painful start for M\u00fcller, Rib\u00e9ry\u2019s role open|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=26 May 2010|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref> M\u00fcller only received superficial injuries and made the final cut for the tournament when the squad was reduced to 23 players.<ref name=\"WCsquad\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8664938.stm|publisher=BBC|title=World Cup 2010: Germany omit Andreas Beck from squad|date=1 June 2010|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref> He was allocated the [[Squad number (association football)|number]] 13,<ref name=\"number13\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/525895/artikel_Mueller-erhaelt-Ballacks-Nummer.html|title=M\u00fcller erh\u00e4lt Ballacks Nummer|work=kicker|date=1 June 2010|accessdate=1 June 2010|language=German|trans-title=M\u00fcller takes Ballack's number}}</ref> normally worn by injured [[Captain (association football)|captain]] [[Michael Ballack]],<ref name=\"number13\" /> and previously worn by M\u00fcller's eponym [[Gerd M\u00fcller|Gerd]].<ref name=\"number13\" /> He earned his second international cap in the final warm-up match before the World Cup when he came on as a half-time substitute for [[Piotr Trochowski]] in a 3\u20131 win over [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/intwettbewerbe/fussball-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2010/4/995257/spielbericht_deutschland_bosnien-herzegowina.html|title=Deutschland \u2013 Bosnien-Herzegowina 3:1|language=German|work=kicker|date=3 June 2010|accessdate=4 June 2010|trans-title=Germany 3\u20131 Bosnia-Herzegovina}}</ref> He started the first game of Germany's World Cup campaign and scored the third goal \u2013 his first internationally \u2013 in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group D#Germany vs Australia|4\u20130 win]] over [[Australia national football team|Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249722/match=300111116/report.html|title=Germany \u2013 Australia|publisher=FIFA|date=13 June 2010|accessdate=14 June 2010}}</ref> winning Germany's goal of the month award in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportschau.de/sp/tor_des_monats/html/popup.php5?show=details&id=480&cb=chronik|title=ARD Sportschau \u2013 Tor des Monats \u2013 Tor des Monats Juni 2010|trans-title=ARD Sports show \u2013 Goal of the Month June 2010|publisher=[[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]]|date=June 2010|accessdate=28 August 2011|language=German}}</ref> He played in all Germany's group games, as they finished top of [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]]; he scored twice and assisted once in the [[Germany v England (2010)#Germany vs England|4\u20131 victory]] over [[England national football team|England]] in the round of 16.<ref name=\"england\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249717/match=300061501/report.html|title=Germany \u2013 England 4:1|publisher=FIFA|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=27 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307144519/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round%3D249717/match%3D300061501/report.html|archivedate=7 March 2011}}</ref> In the third minute of Germany's 4\u20130 [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Argentina vs Germany|quarter final]] win against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], he opened the scoring with his fourth tournament goal.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249718/match=300061505/report.html|title=Argentina \u2013 Germany|publisher=FIFA|date=3 July 2010|accessdate=3 July 2010}}</ref> However, he picked up his second booking of the tournament in the first half, for a [[Handball (soccer)|handball]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/wm/spielplan/weltmeisterschaft/2010/5/833353/spielschema_argentinien_deutschland.html|title=Argentina \u2013 Germany 0:4|work=kicker|date=3 July 2010|accessdate=3 July 2010|language=German|trans-title=Argentina 0\u20134 Germany}}</ref> and was suspended for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs Spain|semi-final defeat]] against [[Spain national football team|Spain]]. M\u00fcller said that he felt far more nervous during the Spain game than any he was able to play.<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> He returned to the team for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Third place play-off|third-place playoff]] against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and scored the first goal, his fifth of the tournament, as Germany won 3\u20132 to take the bronze medals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249720/match=300061510/report.html|title=Uruguay \u2013 Germany|publisher=FIFA|date=20 July 2010|accessdate=10 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307110107/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round%3D249720/match%3D300061510/report.html|archivedate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The team's success was a culmination of a series of changes made after the national team's failure at [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]]. The Germans emphasized a more open, attack-minded style not previously associated with Germany, and included prominent young players, including M\u00fcller, [[Sami Khedira]] and [[Mesut \u00d6zil]].<ref name=\"rafaSI\">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/soccer/world-cup-2010/writers/raphael_honigstein/07/01/germany.reinvention/index.html|title=How Germany reinvented itself|publisher=Sports Illustrated|date=2 July 2010|accessdate=10 August 2011 | first = Raphael | last = Honigstein | authorlink = Raphael Honigstein}}</ref>\n\nWith five goals M\u00fcller ended as joint top [[2010 FIFA World Cup statistics#Goalscorers|goalscorer]] of the tournament. He earned the [[World Cup Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] with these goals and his three [[2010 FIFA World Cup statistics#Assists|assists]].<ref name=\"goldenboot2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/awards/goldenboot/index.html|title=Golden Boot|publisher=FIFA|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=11 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317212405/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/awards/goldenboot/index.html|archivedate=17 March 2012}}</ref> He also won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Best Young Player Award|Best Young Player Award]] over fellow nominees [[Andr\u00e9 Ayew]] of [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and [[Giovani dos Santos]] of [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].<ref name=\"youngplayer2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/awards/bestyoungplayer/news/newsid=1272513/index.html|title= Muller claims two coveted crowns|publisher=FIFA|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> For both awards, he succeeded a German teammate, [[Miroslav Klose]] and [[Lukas Podolski]], respectively, from [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/wm/startseite/527485/artikel_Mueller_Torschuetzenkoenig-und-Bester-Junger-Spieler.html|title=M\u00fcller: Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nig und \"Bester Junger Spieler\"|language=German|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=12 July 2010|work=kicker|trans-title=M\u00fcller top goalscorer and best young player}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, he was named on the [[2010 FIFA Ballon d'Or|shortlist]] for the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]] award along with four of his Germany teammates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/releases/newsid=1323915.html|title=Shortlists for first FIFA Ballon d\u2019Or gala revealed|publisher=FIFA|date=26 October 2010|accessdate=28 October 2010}}</ref> Reflecting on his World Cup success, M\u00fcller said \"I basically got lucky, I hit form at just the right time\".<ref name=\"2010review\" />\n\n===Euro 2012===\nM\u00fcller started all ten of Germany's [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|qualifiers]] for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], as the team qualified for the finals with a 100% record. M\u00fcller provided assists for seven goals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/2011/ |publisher=fussballdaten.de |title=Spiele von Thomas M\u00fcller in 2010/2011| language = German |accessdate=12 October 2010}}</ref> three of which came in a 6\u20132 win over [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in September 2011 which secured Germany's qualification for the finals with two games to spare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/em/qualifikation/em-qualifikation/2010-11/9/999641/spielschema_deutschland_oesterreich.html|title=Deutschland \u2013 \u00d6sterreich 6:2, EM-Qualifikation, Saison 2010/11, 9.Spieltag \u2013 Spielanalyse, Aufstellung, Torsch\u00fctzen und alle Infos zur Spielpaarung|trans-title=Germany 6\u20132 Austria, European Championship qualification, season 2010\u201311, matchday 9 \u2013 Match analysis, line-ups and all match information|language=German|publisher=kicker|date=2 September 2011|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> He scored three times in the campaign, two goals coming in a 4\u20130 win over [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] in March 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/em/qualifikation/em-qualifikation/2010-11/5/999631/spielbericht_deutschland_kasachstan.html|title=Deutschland \u2013 Kasachstan 4:0, EM-Qualifikation, Saison 2010/11, 5.Spieltag|work=kicker|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=26 March 2011|language=German|trans-title=Germany 4\u20130 Kazakhstan, Euro 2012 qualification, matchday 5}}</ref> the third in a 3\u20131 win over [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in October of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/em/qualifikation/em-qualifikation/2010-11/11/999651/spielbericht_tuerkei_deutschland.html|title=Gomez bringt Deutschlands Rekordj\u00e4ger auf Kurs|trans-title=Gomez keeps Germany's record-breakers on course|publisher=kicker|language=German|date= 7 October 2011|accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nM\u00fcller was included in Joachim L\u00f6w's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], where the Germans were knocked out in the semi-finals by [[Italy national football team|Italy]].\n\n===2014 World Cup===\n[[File:Germany players celebrate winning the 2014 FIFA World Cup.jpg|thumb|right|M\u00fcller (#13) celebrating with Germany after winning the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].]]\nM\u00fcller scored his first [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualifying]] goals on 22 March 2013, scoring Germany's opener and final goal in a 3\u20130 away win over [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/us/en/report/334694/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5901 |title= Kazakhstan 0\u20133 Germany |publisher=ESPN FC |date=22 March 2013 | accessdate = 2 April 2013}}</ref> He also scored in the 3\u20130 victories over Austria and the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] to give him four goals in Germany's successful qualification campaign.\n\nOn 16 June 2014, in Germany's opening match of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]],<ref name=\"World Cup: Thomas Mueller scores hat trick as Germany routs Portugal\">{{cite news|last1=Starcevic|first1=Nesha|title=World Cup: Thomas Mueller scores hat trick as Germany routs Portugal|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/worldcup/2014/06/16/world_cup_thomas_mueller_scores_hat_trick_as_germany_routs_portugal.html|accessdate=16 June 2014|agency=The Associated Press|publisher=Toronto Star|date=16 June 2014|location=Salvador, Brazil}}</ref> M\u00fcller scored the first hat-trick of the tournament and was named man of the match in a 4\u20130 win against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref name=\"Germany 4-0 Portugal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285106|title=Germany 4\u20130 Portugal|date=16 June 2014|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=BBC | first = David | last = Ornstein}}</ref> In addition, he was also the target of [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]]'s headbutt in the 37th minute, which resulted in the Portuguese defender being sent off.<ref name=\"World Cup: Thomas Mueller scores hat trick as Germany routs Portugal\"/><ref name=\"Germany 4-0 Portugal\"/> He denied that he had \"overplayed\" the situation leading to the red card.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Uersfeld|first1=Stephan|title=Muller: I didn't influence Pepe red|url=http://www.espnfc.us/germany/story/1886389/germanys-thomas-muller-denies-seeking-to-get-portugal-defender-pepe-dismissed|accessdate=17 June 2014|publisher=ESPN FC|date=16 June 2014}}</ref> On 26 June, M\u00fcller scored the only goal of the final group match against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] to help the Germans win [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] and dispelled fear of collusion between German coach Joachim L\u00f6w and American coach J\u00fcrgen Klinsmann to play to a draw as had occurred in [[Disgrace of Gijon|1982]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/319259.html | title = Mueller goal wins it but USA make history | publisher = ESPN | date = 26 June 2014 | accessdate = 26 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 July, he scored Germany's opening goal in the 7\u20131 [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Semi-final|semi-final]] [[Brazil v Germany (2014 FIFA World Cup)|defeat of Brazil]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knight|first1=Ben|title=Germany demolish Brazil in surreal World Cup semifinal|url=http://www.dw.de/germany-demolish-brazil-in-surreal-world-cup-semifinal/a-17768416|accessdate=9 July 2014|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=8 July 2014}}</ref> This goal was Germany's 2,000th goal in its history. M\u00fcller has now scored at least five goals in each of his first two World Cups, making him only the third player to do so (after [[Te\u00f3filo Cubillas]] and teammate Miroslav Klose).<ref name=\"Brazil vs Germany, World Cup 2014: as it happened\">{{cite news|last1=Tyers|first1=Alan|title=Brazil vs Germany, World Cup 2014: as it happened|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/10951334/Brazil-vs-Germany-World-Cup-2014-as-it-happened.html|accessdate=9 July 2014|publisher=The Telegraph|date=9 July 2014}}</ref> With the goal, he has tied [[Helmut Rahn]] with 10 World Cup goals.<ref name=\"Brazil vs Germany, World Cup 2014: as it happened\"/>\n\nOn 11 July, M\u00fcller was named on the ten-man shortlist for FIFA's [[2014 FIFA World Cup#Golden Ball|Golden Ball]] award for the tournament's best player.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28274011|title=World Cup 2014: Fifa announces Golden Ball shortlist|date=11 July 2014|accessdate=12 July 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> Having played a major role in the team's World Cup triumph, M\u00fcller received the [[FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe#Golden Boot|Silver Boot]] as the tournament's second top goalscorer with five goals,<ref name=FIFAWCSB&SB /><ref name=FIFAWCSB&SB2 /> and was also named in the [[FIFA World Cup Golden Shoe#All-Star Team|World Cup All Star XI]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/awards/golden-boot/index.html | title = adidas Golden Boot | publisher = FIFA.com | accessdate = 16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2016===\nM\u00fcller featured in nine of ten matches during Germany's qualifying campaign for [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying|UEFA Euro 2016]], scoring nine goals as Germany topped their qualifying group to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/european-championship-qualifying/story/2658450/germany-and-poland-qualify-for-euro-2016-ireland-to-playoff|title=Germany, Poland seal Euro 2016 qualification; Ireland to playoff|date=11 October 2015|work=ESPN|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nM\u00fcller started in all six matches that Germany played at the Euro 2016 finals. In the quarter-final match against Italy,<ref name=\"Germany 1\u20131 Italy\u2013Euro 2016\">{{cite news|last1=McNulty|first1=Phil|title=Germany 1 1 Italy|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36628245|accessdate=2 July 2016|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 July 2016}}</ref> M\u00fcller's shot was the first one to be saved in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] during the tournament.<ref name=\"Germany 1\u20131 Italy\u2013Euro 2016\"/> This was the first time Germany failed to score in a shootout since [[Uli Stielike]] missed in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]].<ref name=\"Germany 1\u20131 Italy\u2013Euro 2016\"/> Germany ended up winning the shootout 6\u20135.<ref name=\"Germany 1\u20131 Italy\u2013Euro 2016\"/> M\u00fcller's poor run of form throughout the tournament hurt Germany's chances. Eventually, M\u00fcller finished the tournament without adding a goal to his name at the Euros.\n\n===2018 World Cup===\nM\u00fcller was selected in Germany's final 23-man squad by manager Joachim L\u00f6w for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germany-announce-final-world-cup-squad-with-manuel-neuer-without-leroy-san%C3%A9/a-44064011|title=Germany announce final World Cup squad, with Manuel Neuer, without Leroy San\u00e9|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> M\u00fcller played in all three matches for Germany against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] and [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]. M\u00fcller started against Mexico and Sweden, but came on as a substitute against South Korea. M\u00fcller did not manage to score a goal as Germany crashed out of the World Cup at the group stage.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/321722/ | title = Thomas M\u00fcller | publisher = fifa.com | accessdate = 13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2019, national team coach [[Joachim L\u00f6w]] confirmed that he would plan without M\u00fcller for the foreseeable future, along with his club teammates [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Boateng]] and [[Mats Hummels]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/loew-plant-ohne-mueller-hummels-und-boateng-199284/ |title=L\u00f6w plant ohne M\u00fcller, Hummels, Boateng |trans-title=L\u00f6w plans without M\u00fcller, Hummels, Boateng |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019 |language=German}}</ref> M\u00fcller said after the decision that he was \"angry and surprised\" why L\u00f6w decided to drop him and his Bayern teammates.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/06/thomas-muller-angry-joachim-low-germany-mats-hummels-jerome-boateng-bayern | title = Thomas M\u00fcller 'angry' after Joachim L\u00f6w says he has no Germany future | publisher = theguardian.com | accessdate = 27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nM\u00fcller's role can be described as an attacking all-rounder,<ref name=\"rafaSI\" /> a player able to play in a variety of forward positions. As he came through the [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|youth system]], he was seen primarily as a [[midfielder]],<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> but since breaking into the first-team he has been used in more forward roles. Both Bayern Munich and the Germany national team usually play a [[Formation (association football)#4.E2.80.932.E2.80.933.E2.80.931|4\u20132\u20133\u20131]] formation, and M\u00fcller is most often part of the three attacking midfielders behind the central [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]. He can play in any of the attacking midfield roles but usually plays in the centre for Bayern,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/548672/artikel_stimmungsschwankungen-bei-den-bayern.html|title=Stimmungsschwankungen bei den Bayern|trans-title=Mood swings at Bayern|language=German|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=13 September 2011|publisher=kicker}}</ref> and on the right for Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/klose-impressed-by-new-generation-2018688.html|title=Klose impressed by new generation|date=5 July 2010|accessdate=7 September 2011|publisher=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> He has been used as an out-and-out striker on occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2010-11/16/1013374/spielanalyse_bayern-muenchen-14_fc-st-pauli-18.html|title=Bayern M\u00fcnchen \u2013 FC St. Pauli 3:0, 1. Bundesliga, Saison 2010/11, 16.Spieltag \u2013 Spielanalyse|work=kicker|date=11 December 2010|accessdate=1 January 2011|language=German|trans-title=Bayern Munich 3\u20130 St. Pauli, Bundesliga season 2010\u201311}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he lacks physical strength,<ref name=\"Ancelotti on Muller's role\"/> M\u00fcller has been praised for his maturity,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/news/2010/23893.php|title=Thomas following in Gerd\u2019s footsteps|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> pace, technique,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/news/2010/23785.php|title=Rooney joins in chorus of praise for M\u00fcller|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=16 June 2010|accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> awareness, tactical intelligence, and positioning.<ref name=\"2010review\" /><ref name=\"Ancelotti on Muller's role\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/bayern-munich/story/3040455/carlo-ancelotti-on-thomas-mullers-bayern-munich-role-im-not-stupid|title=Carlo Ancelotti on Thomas Muller's Bayern Munich role: I'm not stupid|publisher=ESPN FC|date=18 January 2017|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> He has been particularly noted for his composure; Germany manager Joachim L\u00f6w said he is \"impervious to pressure\"<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> and former Bayern manager Louis van Gaal said he has tremendous mental strength.<ref name=\"2010review\" /> A consistent scorer and creator of goals,<ref name=\"fussballdaten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/spieler/muellerthomas/|title=Thomas M\u00fcller|publisher=fussballdaten.de|accessdate=24 April 2010|language=German}}</ref> he describes himself as a player who can find gaps in the opposition [[Defender (association football)|defence]] but not particularly good at dribbling or one-on-ones.<ref name=\"champions1210\" /> M\u00fcller describes this role as ''Raumdeuter'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/thomas-mueller-im-gespraech-ich-bin-ein-raumdeuter-1.1043798 | title = Thomas M\u00fcller im Gespr\u00e4ch | language = German | publisher = S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung | date = 9 January 2011 | accessdate = 4 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/james-rodriguez-lewandowski-muller-german-soccer-positions-explained-465557.jsp|title=James Rodriguez as 'Zehner'? Thomas M\u00fcller the 'Raumdeuter'? German soccer positions explained...|publisher=Bundesliga|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=29 October 2018|language=en}}</ref> a term that translates to \"interpreter of space\" ({{abbr|cf.|compare}} ''Traumdeuter'', \"dream interpreter\"). During 2014 World Cup, Germany manager Joachim L\u00f6w stated that M\u00fcller \"is a very unorthodox player and you can't really predict his lines of running, but he has one aim and that is 'how can I score a goal?\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285228|title=2014 Worldcup Germany-Ghana match preview|publisher=BBC|date=21 June 2014|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nM\u00fcller was born in [[Weilheim in Oberbayern|Weilheim]], [[Upper Bavaria]], and grew up in the nearby village of [[P\u00e4hl]], which became the centre of media attention during his World Cup exploits.<ref name=\"sdz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/muenchen/sport/nationalmannschaft-thomas-mueller-paehl-feiert-seinen-wm-helden-1.959572|title=Thomas M\u00fcller \u2013 P\u00e4hl feiert seinen WM-Helden|publisher=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]|language=German|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=4 August 2011|trans-title=Thomas M\u00fcller \u2013 P\u00e4hl celebrates its World Cup hero}}</ref> His parents are Klaudia and Gerhard, and he has a brother, Simon, who is two and a half years younger.<ref name=\"sdz\" /> He married his long-time girlfriend Lisa Trede, a semi-professional equestrian who works on a farm,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sueddeutsche.de/muenchen/thomas-muellers-ehefrau-lisa-pferde-statt-prada-1.1389655 | title = Pferde statt Prada | language = de | publisher = sueddeutsche.de | date = 22 June 2012 | accessdate = 15 July 2014 | first = Stefan | last = Galler}}</ref> in December 2009 after being engaged for two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/de/aktuell/news/2009/21594.php|title=Thomas M\u00fcller unter der Haube|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=2 December 2009|accessdate=10 July 2010|language=German|trans-title=Thomas M\u00fcller ties the knot}}</ref> In June 2011, he became an ambassador for ''YoungWings'', a charity that helps children who have suffered [[bereavement]] or trauma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.telekom.de/en/news/news/2011/29858.php|title=M\u00fcller takes up role as YoungWings ambassador|publisher=Bayern Munich|date=20 June 2011|accessdate=23 June 2011}}</ref> He is [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sport1.de/fussball/dfb-team/2016/11/thomas-mueller-spricht-vor-papst-besuch-ueber-religion | title = M\u00fcller: \"Religion geh\u00f6rt dazu\" | language = de | website = Sport1 | date = 8 November 2016 | access-date = 13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played on 8 March 2020.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club!!rowspan=\"2\"|Season!!colspan=\"3\"|League!!colspan=\"2\"|Cup!!colspan=\"2\"|Continental!!colspan=\"2\"|Other!!colspan=\"2\"|Total!!rowspan=\"2\"|{{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]||[[2007\u201308 Regionalliga#South|2007\u201308]]||[[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1994-2012)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]\n|3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||1\n|<ref name=\"2007\u201308 season\"/>\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 FC Bayern Munich II season|2008\u201309]]||[[3. Liga]]\n|32||15||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||15\n|<ref name=\"Spieler-Statistik 2008/09\"/><ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\"/>\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!35!!16!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!35!!16!!\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=\"13\"|[[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]||[[2008\u201309 FC Bayern Munich season|2008\u201309]]||rowspan=\"12\"|[[Bundesliga]]\n|4||0||0||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\">Appearances in the [[UEFA Champions League]].</ref>||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||1\n|<ref name=\"Spieler-Statistik 2008/09\"/><ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\"/>\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 FC Bayern Munich season|2009\u201310]]\n|34||13||6||4||12<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||52||19\n|<ref name=\"2009\u201310 season\"/>\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 FC Bayern Munich season|2010\u201311]]\n|34||12||5||3||8<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||3||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"German Super Cup\">Appearances in the [[DFL-Supercup|German Super Cup]].</ref>||1||48||19\n|<ref name=\"2010\u201311 season\"/><ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\"/>\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 FC Bayern Munich season|2011\u201312]]||34||7||5||2||14<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||53||11||<ref name=\"2011\u201312 season\"/>\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 FC Bayern Munich season|2012\u201313]]\n|28||13||5||1||13<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||8||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"German Super Cup\"/>||1||47||23\n|<ref name=\"2012\u201313 season\"/><ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\"/>\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 FC Bayern Munich season|2013\u201314]]\n|31||13||5||8||12<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||5||3<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in the [[DFL-Supercup|German Super Cup]], [[UEFA Super Cup]], and [[FIFA Club World Cup]].</ref>||0||51||26\n|<ref name=\"Thomas M\u00fcller \u00bb Club matches\"/><ref name=\"2013\u201314 season\"/>\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 FC Bayern Munich season|2014\u201315]]||32||13||5||1||10<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEFA Champions League\"/>||7||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"German Super Cup\"/>||0||48||21\